#### **Day 45: The Fetch API (Connecting to the World)**
```markdown
# Day 45: Making HTTP Requests with Fetch

**Date:** [Insert Date]

**Topics Covered:**
1. The `fetch()` function.
2. HTTP Methods (GET by default).
3. Handling the Response object (converting stream to JSON).
4. Displaying API data on the HTML page.

**Learning Summary:**
Today is a milestone. I connected my frontend to a real API using `fetch()`. I learned that fetch returns a Promise. The response comes in two stages: first, the headers arrive (we check status), and then we parse the body using `.json()`. I fetched dummy data from `jsonplaceholder` and displayed it.

**Code Snippet:**
```javascript
const url = "[https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1](https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1)";

async function loadData() {
    try {
        const response = await fetch(url);
        
        // Check if server responded with 200 OK
        if (!response.ok) throw new Error("Status code: " + response.status);

        const data = await response.json();
        console.log("Title:", data.title);
        
        // Update DOM
        document.getElementById("output").innerText = data.title;
        
    } catch (error) {
        console.error("Fetch failed:", error);
    }
}

loadData();
